Seems like a plausible idea, with ideas of Nc2, however, White can soon drive the knight away - 11...f5, however, is a safe defensive option that keeps White at bay.

White is trying to push himself away from the action, but it was time to create action of his own with 13. Nxg6! then 13...hxg6 14. Qxg6+ Kh8 15. Qh5+ Kg8 and White has a good attack for the material deficit.
Probably maybe 13...Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne2 15. Qe3 Nxc3 works out better for Black.
White misses 14. Bh6 g5 15. a3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nb3 with a slight advantage
Seems logical to trade off the menacing bishop, but 14...Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne2 16. Qf3 Nxc3 - wins a pawn and keeps a dangerous knight on - making White having to think both defense and attack.
Bh6, starting the attack might have been simpler.
Ambiguous - Still, Bh6 wasn't too late.

Certainly the last time to play Bh6.
